The paper deals with the task of acoustic emotion recognition, which involves analyzing speech signals to categorize the affective state of the speaker. This task is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including speech processing (cs.SD), natural language processing (cs.CL), machine learning (cs.LG), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Given that the paper proposes a set of architectures that utilize neural representations inferred by training on large speech databases, it is likely to be relevant to these sub-fields.
